text: @pkarnezis @RogerGalligan @CDCgov Each age group is separate. In each age group it’s just “what fraction of tests were positive for COVID-19”? Essentially the middle panel divided by the left panel. It shouldn’t add up to 100%.

Follow up #2: Here's a more complete figure showing specimens tested, confirmed cases and fraction of specimens testing positive across age groups. Again, data is directly from @CDCgov's COVIDView. https://t.co/yPf5OnR5mL

With "reopening", we may see this trend in age distribution continue. This should ameliorate some of the health impacts of COVID-19, but will necessarily only go so far. There is no way to completely isolate vulnerable individuals from a widespread epidemic. 10/10

Here, I downloaded COVIDView data and slightly prettified their plots. If we look at testing in commercial labs, we see that across confirmed cases, there are slightly more cases in the 0 to 49 year demographic than there were in April. 6/10 https://t.co/0jViHPjtdb

However, given what know about severity vs age, we really want to understand what's going on across different age groups. After digging around, the only source I could find that splits confirmed cases by age through time is @CDCgov's COVIDView (https://t.co/7IJVEniaLa). 5/10

Consistent with this, we see from @COVID19Tracking that nationally test positivity has shrunk. 4/10
https://t.co/lvnDrwru2Y

A small follow up to the "long plateau" assessment of the #COVID19 epidemic. When I tweeted this on April 30, we had ~30k daily confirmed cases and ~2000 daily deaths. This last week, we had ~24k daily confirmed cases and ~700 daily deaths. 1/10
https://t.co/SjLdYVZdhK

@MyMicroreact @CovidGenomicsUK This is really cool! I'm very impressed. I'm of course curious how you accomplished the performance improvements. Is this a new version of phylocanvas more recent than v2.8.1? (This is what I see on GitHub / https://t.co/QHqkXFgRjs)

The relative scarcity of children recorded with confirmed cases of #COVID19 has been remarked on repeatedly. However, I actually hadn't noticed until today that SARS in Hong Kong in 2003 also showed a scarcity (from @gmleunghku et al https://t.co/mKM0yHegYz). 1/2 https://t.co/fXUZqTptP3

I thought to look into a specific state and start with Arizona. Here, we see pretty dramatic increases in confirmed cases starting about May 26. Arizona's stay-at-home order expired on May 15. Figure from the @azdhs COVID-19 data dashboard. 2/10 https://t.co/5unV2Iqu52

As many have noted, there has been an uptick in confirmed #COVID19 cases in multiple states starting roughly at the beginning of June. There is a major question surrounding how much "re-opening" efforts are contributing to increases in transmission. Figure from @nytimes. 1/10 https://t.co/lwUyrWrSug

@NathanGrubaugh My intent was certainly not to blame protesters for COVID transmission. I was laying out what I believe to be a significant risk that should be considered and to describe actions that can be taken by police and by protesters to mitigate against.

Given the severity of COVID-19, even a modest increase of 3% to 6% on top of the current national epidemic has substantial downstream repercussions. 10/12
